────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
RAIDS OF UMM'NATUR — PIXELLAB TERRAIN TILE GUIDE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

WHY THIS IS HARD
────────────────
PixelLab generates a square image. The game UV-maps that square onto a flat-top
hexagon. This means:

  1. The four corners of the square are NEVER rendered — wasted pixels.
  2. The six straight edges of the hex are where adjacent tiles meet.
  3. Adjacent tiles sample DIFFERENT UV regions along a shared border — one
     tile's right-edge pixels sit next to the other tile's left-edge pixels.
     They will never be identical, so the ONLY way edges blend is if both tiles
     share the same general tone/color in that zone.

The hex boundary in a 128×128 image (flat-top, circumradius = 64px):

    Vertex positions (x, y):
      Right:        (128,  64)
      Bottom-right: ( 96, 120)
      Bottom-left:  ( 32, 120)
      Left:         (  0,  64)
      Top-left:     ( 32,   8)
      Top-right:    ( 96,   8)

    Invisible corner triangles (approximate):
      Top-left:     (0,0)→(0,64)→(32,8)
      Top-right:    (128,0)→(96,8)→(128,64)
      Bottom-left:  (0,128)→(32,120)→(0,64)
      Bottom-right: (128,128)→(128,64)→(96,120)

    Each corner triangle is roughly 12–14% of the total square area.
    Anything you put in those triangles is invisible in-game.


ZONE RULES
──────────
Divide the tile into three zones:

  [EDGE ZONE]   — outer ring, ~20px inward from the hex boundary
                  Must be plain, low-contrast texture with the terrain's
                  dominant base color. No distinctive shapes, no hard
                  color transitions. Think of it as the "grout" between tiles.

  [MID ZONE]    — the ring between edge and center
                  Gentle variation — subtle pebbles, faint ripples, light
                  shading. Nothing that would read as a "feature."

  [CENTER ZONE] — inner circle, roughly radius 30px around pixel (64,64)
                  The only place for landmark detail: a rock cluster, a ruin
                  fragment, a palm tree, a pool. Keep it contained and readable.

Visual summary (schematic for a 128×128 tile):

        ╔═══════════════════╗
        ║ invisible corner  ║
        ║   ╱───────────╲   ║
        ║  / EDGE ZONE   \  ║
        ║ │  ┌─────────┐  │ ║
        ║ │  │ MID     │  │ ║
        ║ │  │  ┌───┐  │  │ ║
        ║ │  │  │CTR│  │  │ ║
        ║ │  │  └───┘  │  │ ║
        ║ │  └─────────┘  │ ║
        ║  \ EDGE ZONE   /  ║
        ║   ╲───────────╱   ║
        ║ invisible corner  ║
        ╚═══════════════════╝


COLOR PALETTES (Egyptian desert — Umm'Natur)
─────────────────────────────────────────────
Keep each terrain's edges in its designated base color range. Variants of the
same terrain must share the same base color — only the center detail differs.

  Sand      base #C4935A–#E8C07A  highlight #F2D89A  shadow #9B6B3A
  Dune      base #D4870A–#E8A030  highlight #F0C060  shadow #A05810
  Rock      base #8B7355–#A0896A  highlight #C0A87A  shadow #5A4530
  Mountain  base #7A5C3A–#9A7250  highlight #B08A60  shadow #4A3520
  Oasis     base #3A7A2A–#5A9A40  water #2A6080–#4A90B0   sand edge same as Sand
  Ruins     base #B09060–#C8A870  stone #9A8258–#B09A70    sand edge same as Sand
  Obsidian  base #1A1A2A–#2A2A3A  highlight #3A3A5A  edge hint #0A0A15
  River     base #2A6080–#3A80A0  bank #C4935A (same as Sand)
  Wall      base #6A5A4A–#8A7A6A  mortar #4A3A2A
  Battle    base #C4935A (same as Sand, with scorch marks in center only)


WHAT GOOD PROMPTS DO
─────────────────────
✓  State the hex crop constraint explicitly
✓  Specify the base color by hex value
✓  Demand uniform edges / uniform corners
✓  Put all detail in the center
✓  Specify 128×128 and pixel art style
✓  Reference the lighting direction: soft top-left ambient, flat overhead

What to AVOID in prompts:
✗  "seamless tileable" — AI interprets this as left↔right repeating texture,
     not what we need. We need uniform-toned edges, not tiling.
✗  Asking for "detailed edges" or "border decoration"
✗  Any prompt that might produce a frame/vignette (the old sand2 problem)
✗  "isometric" — we're top-down flat overhead, not isometric


PROVEN PROMPT TEMPLATE
───────────────────────
Use this template as the base, fill in [TERRAIN], [BASE_COLOR], [CENTER_DETAIL]:

  128x128 pixel art terrain tile for a flat-top hex strategy game with an
  Egyptian desert theme. Top-down overhead view, flat lighting from above.

  The game engine masks this image to a hex shape at runtime — do NOT draw
  a hexagon. Fill the entire square with terrain. The four corners of the
  square are hidden in-game so treat them as throwaway fill.

  EDGE RULE: the outer 20 pixels along all four sides of the square must be
  plain flat [BASE_COLOR] with very subtle fine-grain texture only. No patterns,
  no shapes, no shadows that touch the image edge. This is the single most
  important rule — it determines whether tiles blend on the map.

  CENTER DETAIL: [CENTER_DETAIL] — contained within the central 60×60 pixel
  area of the image only.

  Base color: [BASE_COLOR]. Overall feel: dry, ancient, warm-toned desert.
  Clean pixel art, limited palette (~16 colors), no anti-aliasing blur.


EXAMPLE FILLED PROMPTS
───────────────────────

SAND (plain variant):
  128x128 pixel art terrain tile for a flat-top hex strategy game with an
  Egyptian desert theme. Top-down overhead view, flat lighting from above.
  The image will be cropped to a hexagon — corners are invisible, fill them
  with plain warm sand color #D4A862.
  EDGE RULE: outer 20px on all sides must be flat uniform sandy ground
  #D4A862 with very faint fine-grain texture only. No patterns near edges.
  CENTER DETAIL: subtle scattered fine sand grains and two or three tiny
  pebbles, centrally placed.
  Base color: #D4A862 warm sandy tan. Clean pixel art, ~16 color palette.

SAND (cracked earth variant):
  [same header and edge rule as above]
  CENTER DETAIL: small patch of dry cracked earth in a sun-star pattern,
  centered at pixel (64,64), radius ~25px. Cracks are dark brown #7A4A20.
  Surrounding area plain sandy #D4A862.

DUNE (ridge variant):
  [same header and crop rule]
  Base color: #D4870A–#E8A030 golden orange.
  EDGE RULE: outer 20px flat golden sand #D4870A.
  CENTER DETAIL: one smooth sand dune ridge curving through the center of
  the image. Ridge highlight #F0C060, shadow side #A05810. Ridge is fully
  contained within the central 80×80 pixels — no ridge line touches image edge.

OASIS:
  [same header and crop rule]
  Base color: #C4935A sandy ground (matching Sand tiles for edge blending).
  EDGE RULE: outer 20px must be plain sandy #C4935A — identical in tone to
  the Sand terrain so oasis tiles blend with surrounding desert.
  CENTER DETAIL: a small turquoise pool #3A80A0 radius ~20px surrounded by
  two palm trees (dark green fronds #2A5A1A), all within central 60×60px.

RUINS:
  [same header and crop rule]
  Base color: #C4935A sandy ground with stone #B09060.
  EDGE RULE: outer 20px plain sandy #C4935A ground, no stone near edges.
  CENTER DETAIL: two or three broken sandstone column stumps and a carved
  floor tile fragment with simple hieroglyph, within central 70×70px.


GENERATION SETTINGS
────────────────────
  Model:   pixflux  (Bitforge for style-transfer experiments)
  Size:    128×128
  Guidance: 8.0–9.0  (higher = prompt adherence, important for edge rules)

  CLI example:
    python3 scripts/pixellab_client.py pixflux \
      "128x128 pixel art ... [full prompt] ..." \
      --size 128x128 --guidance 8.5 \
      --out assets/textures/terrain/sand/sand_cracked.png

  After generating, visually check:
    1. Are the image edges (all four sides) plain and same-toned?
    2. Is all distinctive detail within the central 60×60px area?
    3. Do the corner regions match the edge zone color (they're invisible but
       the AI will generate them, and edge-zone bleed from corners wastes budget)?
    4. Does the color read as the right terrain at a glance?

  KNOWN FAILURE MODE — "draws a hexagon":
  If the prompt mentions "hexagon" too prominently, the AI literally draws a
  hexagon shape in the center of the image. Avoid describing the crop geometry
  in the prompt at all. Instead, just tell it to keep edges plain.
  Replace "cropped to a hexagon" with:
    "the game engine masks this image to a hex shape — just fill the entire
     square with terrain and keep the image edges uniform."

  If a tile fails edge rule, regenerate with --guidance 9.0 and add:
  "CRITICAL: image edges must be completely plain uniform terrain color —
  this is the most important requirement. Sacrifice all detail for flat edges."


WORKFLOW FOR NEW VARIANTS
──────────────────────────
1. Write the prompt using the template above.
2. Generate at 128×128.
3. Open the PNG — check edges visually.
4. If edges are bad, tweak prompt (add more emphasis on edge rule) and retry.
5. Drop the PNG into assets/textures/terrain/<name>/ — no code change needed.
6. Launch the game and inspect in the world builder with adjacent tiles placed.
7. If colors clash with neighbors, adjust the base color in the next generation.
